         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">November 18 1894 ¶ Baron Ferd. von Mueller, Melbourne. ¶ My dear Sir, ¶  ¶ I note that when writing to you last ¶ Letter not found. ¶  ¶ I overlooked your question regarding the Monochlamydeae and Pro...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">94.11.18</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Eugene Hilgard</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">C-B 972 letterpress copy books, vol. 20, Bancroft Library, University of California, Berkeley, California.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style=""/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The letterpress copy books contain typed copies of the outgoing letters.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the quality is poor<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and some readings are uncertain.</p>
               </note>November 18 1894</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron Ferd. von Mueller, Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I note that when writing to you last<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I overlooked your question regarding the Monochlamydeae and Prof. E. L. Greene's views on their justification as a natural group.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to E. Hilgard, 13 July 1894.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Prof. Greene is absent on a six months leave and I cannot ask him the question direct; but from the general tenor of his ideas I feel quite sure that he, with pretty nearly all of the advanced botanists of the world, considers Monachlamydeae as mere "Noth behelf"<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>makeshift.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>for a time, the usefulness of which is past. Not only that it is violently heterogenous within itself, but that the affinities of some of the groups with others of the Petalanthae is so obvious that it cannot be ignored. I remember that even in the olden time when I heard lectures on Botany, the professor used to apologize for the monochlamydism and apetalism of ranunculacaeous and rosaceous genera, saying "Man muss es aber damit nicht zu genau nehmen".<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>One must however not take it too exactly.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>An address made at the last meeting of the Amer. Ass'n Adv't of Sci. — I forget by whom — brought out most pointedly the idea, put forth by my brother T. C.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Theodore Charles Hilgard.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>twenty-five years ago, that the several typical groups of orders seem to undergo more or less parallel phases of development, from<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>gamopetalism<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>through<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>polyetalism<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>polypetalism?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and monochlamydism to apetalism, and from hypogynism to epigynism.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Meehan (1894) has a brief section that may be the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>discussion that Hilgard cites.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>My brother once carried this idea out in graphic form, along the lines of a pentagram.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>T. Hilgard (1860).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Of course ideas may differ greatly as to the values to be assigned to the different points in variation; but I think few will maintain that a linear taxonomy can be made satisfactory in any way.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Now, thinking of it, I am not sure that I have told you that you are mistaken about the species of the oak that grows (it has but rarely been planted) on the San Francisco peninsula as well as on this side of the bay being Q.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Quercus.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>chrysolepis. That grows only on the higher portions of the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Coast range and on the flanks of the Sierra Nevada, nor has it been planted to any extent hereabouts although it evidently does fairly well. Q. agrifolia prevails almost exclusively here along the coast; on the landward slopes of Coast ranges it is mixed with Q. Wisliceni<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">Quercus<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">wislizeni</seg>?<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Misreading by Hilgard's clerk?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and Kelloggii (Sonamensis<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn11" n="12">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Q. sonomensis?<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Misreading by Hilgard's clerk?<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>There is<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>no closing ).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and in the valleys with Q. lobata. — This has been a very<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>bad<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>season for acorns all through the state; the caterpillar (Aletia)<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn12" n="13">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A genus of moth.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>has destroyed the foliage and crippled the acorns, so that my foremen in the Sierra foothills doubts that he will be able to obtain good seed of Q. chrysolepis. Here, where last year the ground was covered with acorns at this time, hardly one is to be seen.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We have obtained from Japan a lot of seed of the Polyg. Sachal.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn13" n="14">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Polygonum sachalinense</seg>. For uses, see B98.08.04.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>which is having a "boom" now, together with the Canaigre.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn14" n="15">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For uses, see B98.08.04, under<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Rumex hymenosepalus</seg>; Hilgard is acknowledged as a source of information.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I am just getting out a Bulletin on the latter<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn15" n="16">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>E.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Hilgard (1894), Jaffa (1894).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and on the Atriplex, which will go to you by next mail steamer.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn16" n="17">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There is no signature on the file copy.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Atriplex</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Monochlamydeae</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Petalanthae</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">Polygonum<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">sachalinense</seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Quercus agrifolia</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Quercus chrysolepis</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Quercus Kelloggii</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Quercus lobata</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Quercus Sonamensis</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Quercus Wisliceni</p>
         </div>
